														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4845061">
									

<p>This and All Hallows' are the best things you've written that I have read thus far. I already felt like Anderson wasn't fully a villain. Now you've explored that aspect of him. (Not that he's a <em>good guy</em>, just that you are successful in portraying him as a multi-faceted person enough that I picked up on it before this tale.) You've hit a certain bar that assures that I have warmed up to a character forever; whenever a scene cuts off, I instinctively stop reading and imagine the continuation, or implications as they sprawl. In this case, I had a lot of faux-conversations between Anderson and others, like when he enters Merlo's house, when he says he'll &quot;mull things over&quot; to Shaw, or when he asks again where his brother would like to go. Good, good stuff. Really loving this character.</p>

							</div>

								
					
